[[File:Nikiyama Kofun, haisho.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Mitsuyoshi Mausoleum Reference {{ill|Haisho|ja|拝所|lt=Worship Site|12=draft}}}}]]
'''Nikiyama Kofun''' (新木山古墳) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Kōryō, Nara|ja|広陵町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kitakatsuragi District|ja|北葛城郡|12=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|12=draft}}. This {{ill|Zenpō-kōen-fun|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft}} is part of the {{ill|Umami Kofun Group|ja|馬見古墳群|1=Umami Kofun Cluster|12=draft}} (Central Group).

The actual interred individual is unknown. However, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} manages the site as the "Mitsuyoshi Mausoleum Reference," associating it with Prince Oshisaka no Hikohito no Ōe, the son of {{ill|Emperor Bidatsu|ja|敏達天皇|12=draft}} and father of {{ill|Emperor Jomei|ja|舒明天皇|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==
As the Mitsuyoshi {{ill|Mausoleum Reference|ja|陵墓参考地|1=Mausoleum Reference Site|12=draft}}, the site is under the management of the Imperial Household Agency and is not accessible to the general public.

The kofun was built on a small ridge extending eastward from a lower north-south ridge. Its main axis runs approximately east-west, with {{ill|Tsukuridashi|ja|造り出し|12=draft}} features at both constriction areas. The structure resembles the nearby {{ill|Suyama Kofun|ja|巣山古墳|1=Suyama Kofun|12=draft}}. The moat is approximately 18 meters wide at the rear circular section and 22 meters wide at the front section. The outer embankment, used as field ridges for rice paddies and farmland, is believed to have been about 20 meters wide and over 3 meters high. <ref name=iseki>Kawakami Kunihiko, *"The Large Kofun Groups of Yamato-Katsuragi: The Umami Kofun Group"*, Shinseisha, 2006.</ref>

A line of {{ill|Haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft}} was confirmed on the tumulus. excavations preserved by the Imperial Household Agency include {{ill|Magatama|ja|勾玉|12=draft}}, tubular beads, and natama (small beads). Cylindrical haniwa with square perforations and black mottling date the construction to the early 5th century. <ref name=iseki /> This kofun is the final large-map_size zenpō-kōen-fun of the Umami Kofun Group's Central Group. <ref>"Yamato no Kofun I," p. 73.</ref>

On the west side of the rear circular section lies {{ill|Mitsuyoshi Ishizuka Kofun|ja|三吉石塚古墳|12=draft}}, a {{ill|Hotategai-gata Kofun|ja|帆立貝形古墳|1=Scallop Kofun|12=draft}} aligned along the same axis and constructed adjacent to the outer embankment. <ref>{{Cite web|typeat=PDF|url=https://www.town.koryo.nara.jp/cmsfiles/contents/0000000/26/mitsuyoshiishidukakohun.pdf|title=Mitsuyoshi Ishizuka Kofun & Nikiyama Kofun location map|publisher=Kōryō Town|accessdate=2017-12-25}}</ref>

